SIMPLE: inform
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inform
<hw>In*form"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>informis</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets> not + <ets>forma</ets> form,
shape: cf. F. <ets>informe</ets>]</ety> <def>Without regular form;
shapeless; ugly; deformed.</def> <rj><au>Cotton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inform</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Inform
<hw>In*form"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Informed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Informing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>enformen</ets>, OF.
<ets>enformer</ets>, F. <ets>informer</ets>. L. <ets>informare</ets>;
pref. <ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>formare</ets> to form, share, fr.
<ets>forma</ets> form. See <er>Form</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
give form or share to; to give vital or organizing power to; to give
life to; to imbue and actuate with vitality; to animate; to mold; to
figure; to fashion.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <qex>informing</qex> Word.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let others better mold the running mass⟦br⟧
Of metals, and <qex>inform</qex> the breathing brass.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Breath <qex>informs</qex> this fleeting frame.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Breathes in our soul, <qex>informs</qex> our mortal part.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To communicate knowledge to; to make known to; to
acquaint; to advise; to instruct; to tell; to notify; to enlighten; --
usually followed by <xex>of</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For he would learn their business secretly,⟦br⟧
And then <qex>inform</qex> his master hastily.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am <qex>informed</qex> thoroughly of the cause.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To communicate a knowledge of facts to, by way of
accusation; to warn against anybody.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tertullus . . . <qex>informed</qex> the governor against Paul.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts xxiv. 1.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To acquaint; apprise; tell; teach; instruct;
enlighten; animate; fashion.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inform</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Inform
<hw>In*form"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take form; to
become visible or manifest; to appear.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is the bloody business which <qex>informs</qex>⟦br⟧
Thus to mine eyes.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give intelligence or information; to tell.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He might either teach in the same manner, or <qex>inform</qex> how
he had been taught.</q> <rj><qau>Monthly Rev.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To inform against</b></col>, <cd>to communicate facts by
way of accusation against; to denounce; <as>as, two persons came to the
magistrate, and <ex>informed against</ex> A</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Informal</ent>⟦br⟧
